&lt;p&gt;&lt;tt&gt;--- &quot;C. Paige Gabhart&quot; &lt;pgabhart@...&gt; wrote:&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; Chuck:&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; I think you&#39;ve hit on a valid point.&nbsp; I have read&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; posts by people who seem to think there is a problem&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; with QS&#39;s design because they find it tough&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; going to build up their reading speed.&nbsp; I think they&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; are failing to take into account how much time they&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; have spent in their life reading TO.&nbsp; Even&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; when we don&#39;t intend to read, we are surrounded&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; constantly by advertising and end up reading it.&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt;&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; If we want to gain reading speed in QS, we have to&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; read QS a lot.&nbsp; Your method of rereading several&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; day&#39;s journal entries sounds excellent to me.&nbsp; Of&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; course it would be even better to read other&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; people&#39;s QS.&nbsp; Is there anyone here on the list that&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; could help up us set up a place to write back and&lt;/tt&gt;
&lt;br&gt;&lt;tt&gt;&gt; forth in QS?&lt;/tt&gt;
